T1  - Disentangling the Influences of Leaders' Relational Embeddedness on Interorganizational Exchange
AU  - Barden, Jeffrey Q.
AU  - Mitchell, Will
Y1  - 2007/12/01
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2007.28225983
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2007.28225983
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1440
EP  - 1461
VL  - 50
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Drawing on the concept of relational embeddedness and the associated mechanisms of mutual understanding, trust, and commitment, we examine how leaders' prior exchange experiences influence the likelihood of subsequent interorganizational exchange. We begin to develop a microlevel model of organization-level relations that accounts for nodal multiplexity. In data on baseball player trades, we found that individual leaders' ties affected exchanges less than did an organization's other ties. The sharing of exchange experiences by organizations and their current leaders increased the influences of those experiences on exchange behavior. Thus, leaders have more influence within their organizational contexts than in isolation.
AB  - Drawing on the concept of relational embeddedness and the associated mechanisms of mutual understanding, trust, and commitment, we examine how leaders' prior exchange experiences influence the likelihood of subsequent interorganizational exchange. We begin to develop a microlevel model of organization-level relations that accounts for nodal multiplexity. In data on baseball player trades, we found that individual leaders' ties affected exchanges less than did an organization's other ties. The sharing of exchange experiences by organizations and their current leaders increased the influences of those experiences on exchange behavior. Thus, leaders have more influence within their organizational contexts than in isolation.
